---
title: Stop Asking If It's a Good Time to Buy
description: The question "is now a good time to buy?" creates more hesitation than clarity. Here's a better framework for evaluating whether a property is right for you right now.
publishDate: 2026-01-22
category: first-time-buyers
readTime: 3
---

Most buyers are still trying to answer the same question: Is now a good time to buy?

That question used to be useful when markets moved more clearly in one direction. Today, it tends to create more hesitation than clarity. Prices are uneven, inventory varies by area, and while interest rates still matter, they're no longer the only factor shaping outcomes.

A more useful question is simpler and more durable: **Is this a property I'd feel good owning no matter what happens next?**

## Why Market Timing Fails Most Buyers

The buyers who waited for a "better time" in 2020 paid more in 2021. The buyers who waited for rates to fall in 2023 waited while prices in some Barrie neighbourhoods recovered.

Market timing requires being right twice: when to exit (or not buy) and when to re-enter. Professional investors struggle with this. First-time buyers rarely get it right.

The cost of being wrong is not just the price you pay — it's also the rent you paid while waiting, the equity you didn't build, and in some cases, the stress of watching the opportunity pass.

## A Better Evaluation Framework

Instead of asking "is now a good time to buy," ask:

**1. Does this property work at current rates?**
Run the numbers at today's rate, not a hoped-for future rate. If the payment only works when you assume rates drop by 1.5%, the property doesn't actually work today.

**2. Can I hold it for at least five years?**
Five years is the threshold where Canadian real estate has historically recovered from short-term corrections. If your timeline is shorter, you're speculating, not buying.

**3. Is the property priced reasonably relative to comparable sales — not relative to peak?**
Comparing to 2022 peak prices is not useful. Compare to recent transactions in the same area and property type.

**4. Do the carrying costs fit within 39% of gross household income?**
This is the GDS ratio used by lenders. If housing costs exceed this, the math is strained regardless of what the market does.

**5. Does this solve a real housing need?**
Buying because you need housing is different from buying to speculate. If you need to be housed somewhere anyway, owning at reasonable terms is almost always better than renting indefinitely.

## The Barrie Market Reality

Barrie is not a bubble about to pop. It's a growing mid-sized city with employment diversification, continued population inflow from Toronto, and limited new housing supply relative to demand.

That doesn't mean every property is worth buying. It means the question is about the specific property, not the general market.

